Title: The entorhinal cortex of the monkey: III. Subcortical afferents.
Abstract: The subcortical afferent connections of the entorhinal cortex of the Macaca fascicularis monkey were investigated by the placement of small injections of the retrograde tracer wheat germ agglutinin conjugated to horseradish peroxidase into each of its subdivisions. Retrogradely labeled cells were observed in several subcortical regions including the amygdaloid complex, claustrum, basal forebrain, thalamus, hypothalamus, and brainstem. In the amygdala, labeled cells were observed principally in the lateral nucleus, the accessory basal nucleus, the deep or paralaminar portion of the basal nucleus, and the periamygdaloid cortex. Additional retrogradely labeled cells were found in the endopiriform nucleus, the anterior amygdaloid area, and the cortical nuclei. Retrogradely labeled cells were observed throughout much of the rostrocaudal extent of the claustrum and tended to be located in its ventral half. In the basal forebrain, retrogradely labeled cells were observed in the medial septal nucleus, the nucleus of the diagonal band, and to lesser extent within the substantia innominata. Several of the cells in the latter region were large and located within the densely packed neuronal clusters of the basal nucleus of Meynert. Most of the labeled cells in the thalamus were located in the midline nuclei. Many were found in nucleus reuniens, but even greater numbers were located in the centralis complex. Additional labeled cells were located in the paraventricular and parataenial nuclei. In all cases, numerous retrogradely labeled cells were observed in the medial pulvinar. In the hypothalamus, most of the retrogradely labeled cells were located in the supramamillary area, though scattered cells were also observed in the perifornical region and in the lateral hypothalamic area. Caudal to the mamillary nuclei there were labeled cells in the ventral tegmental area. There were relatively few labeled cells in the brainstem and these were invariably located either in the raphe nuclei or locus coeruleus.

@Methods.Comments:
The methods are not described in detailed form, but a little bit more detailed as for the cases with WGA-HRP.
Citation:" ( ... ) 
Tissue was processed and analyzed as described in Insazsti et al. ( `87 ) and the distribution of anterogradely transported label was analyzed with darkfield optics. " ( p. 397 )

@Injections.Citation: " With injections of the lateral nucleus, labeled terminals and fibers were observed in the deep half of layer I of all divisions of the entorhinal cortex. " (p. 398)
@Injections.Comments: The description of the injection site is not very precise respectively detailed.

@Injections.Citation: " The magnocellular division of the accessory basal nucleus also projects to layer I of the entire entorhinal cortex and, in ER, terminates throughout layer III and in the cell-free interstices of layer II." (p. 398)
" The periamygdaloid cortex projects primarily to rostral levels of the entorhinal cortex and  terminates mainly in layer II and in the superficial portion of layer III. " (p. 398)

@Methods.Comments:
Actually there is no description of the used methods and of their details.
It is only said that the methods are the same as in the companion paper Insausti et al. `87 ( IAC87a ):
"The observations discussed here are derived from the preparations described in detail in a previous paper ( Insausti et al. `87 ) ." ( p. 397 )

@Injections.Citation:
" Injections fo the intermediate (EI) and caudal (EC and ECL) portions of the entorhinal cortex resulted in fewer retrogradely
labeled cells in the amygdala. Experiments with injections located medially at these levels, such as IM-3, M-4-86, and IM-10,
demonstrated a greater number of retrogradely cells than those with lateral injections, such as IM-7."  (p. 398)
@Injections.Comments: The volume of the cases with WGA-HRP injections are taken from the previous paper IAC87a.

@Injections.Citation: " The largest number of retrogradely labeled cells was observed in experiment IM-4. The injection in this case involved the olfactory portion of the entorhinal cortex (EO) but also heavily involved the periamygdaloid cortex and at least the medial aspect of the accessory basal nucleus." (p. 397)
@Injections.Comments: The volume of the cases with WGA-HRP injections are taken from the previous paper IAC87a.

@Injections.Comments: The volume of the cases with WGA-HRP injections are taken from the previous paper IAC87a.
